  "Paper and paperboard": "",
  "Metals": "",
  "Plastics": "",
  "Food waste": "",
  "Paper and paperboard make up the largest component of municipal solid waste by weight in the United States at approximately 23%, followed by food waste and yard trimmings.": "",
  "What federal law governs the disposal of hazardous waste in the United States?": "",
  "National Environmental Policy Act": "",
  "Clean Air Act": "",
  "Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA)": "",
  "Clean Water Act": "",
  "The Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) of 1976 governs the disposal of solid and hazardous waste, establishing a 'cradle-to-grave' system for tracking hazardous waste from generation to final disposal.": "",
  "What is composting?": "",
  "Burning organic waste to generate energy": "",
  "The biological decomposition of organic waste into nutrient-rich soil amendment": "",
  "Chemical treatment of waste to make it harmless": "",
  "Compressing waste into dense blocks for landfill disposal": "",
  "Composting is the controlled aerobic decomposition of organic materials (food scraps, yard waste) by microorganisms into humus, a nutrient-rich soil amendment. It diverts organic waste from landfills and reduces methane emissions.": "",
  "What is 'municipal solid waste (MSW)'?": "",
  "Waste produced only by government buildings": "",
  "Industrial hazardous waste from factories": "",
  "Everyday garbage and recyclables generated by homes, businesses, and institutions in a community": "",
  "Radioactive waste from nuclear power plants": "",
  "Municipal solid waste (MSW) includes everyday items discarded by households, businesses, and institutions such as packaging, food scraps, furniture, clothing, bottles, newspapers, appliances, and yard trimmings.": "",
  "What does 'source reduction' mean in waste management?": "",
  "Reducing the number of waste collection sources in a city": "",
  "Sorting waste at its source before collection": "",
  "Preventing waste from being created in the first place through design changes, reduced packaging, and consumption choices": "",
  "Reducing the size of landfills": "",
  "Source reduction (waste prevention) is the most preferred strategy in the waste hierarchy. It involves designing products with less material, reducing packaging, buying in bulk, and making choices that prevent waste generation.": "",
  "What is 'leachate'?": "",
  "A type of plastic used in landfill liners, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The daily soil cover applied to landfill waste within the broader context of leachate analysis": "",
  "Contaminated liquid that forms when water percolates through waste material, picking up dissolved and suspended pollutants": "",
  "A gas produced by decomposing waste according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Leachate is liquid that percolates through waste in a landfill, dissolving and carrying harmful substances such as heavy metals, organic compounds, and pathogens. Modern landfills collect leachate through drainage systems for treatment.": "",
  "What does 'cradle-to-grave' mean in the context of hazardous waste management?": "",
  "The lifespan of a landfill from opening to closure": "",
  "Burying hazardous waste in underground graves": "",
  "The time it takes for waste to decompose completely": "",
  "A system that tracks hazardous waste from its generation through transportation, treatment, and final disposal": "",
  "Cradle-to-grave is the RCRA's approach to hazardous waste management, requiring documentation and proper handling at every stage from generation (cradle) to final disposal (grave), ensuring accountability throughout the waste's lifecycle.": "",
  "What is a 'sanitary landfill'?": "",
  "A facility that only accepts medical waste": "",
  "An underground chamber for storing radioactive waste": "",
  "An engineered waste disposal facility with liners, leachate collection, gas management, and environmental monitoring systems": "",
  "A clean outdoor area where waste is left to decompose naturally": "",
  "A sanitary landfill is an engineered facility designed to isolate waste from the surrounding environment using impermeable liners, leachate collection and treatment systems, methane gas management, daily soil cover, and groundwater monitoring.": "",
  "What does 'integrated waste management' mean?": "",
  "Using only one method to handle all waste based on the conventional understanding of how waste processes interact in practice": "",
  "A comprehensive approach that combines multiple waste management strategies including reduction, reuse, recycling, composting, incineration, and landfilling": "",
  "Integrating waste management with water treatment when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Mixing all types of waste together for disposal without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Integrated waste management uses a combination of approaches, applying the most appropriate methods for different waste streams according to the waste hierarchy, rather than relying on a single disposal method.": "",
  "What does 'tipping fee' mean in waste management?": "",
  "The charge levied per ton of waste delivered to a landfill or waste processing facility": "",
  "A bonus paid to waste collection workers": "",
  "A tax on recyclable materials": "",
  "The cost of tipping over waste containers for collection": "",
  "A tipping fee is the gate fee charged to waste haulers for each ton of waste delivered to a landfill or waste facility. Higher tipping fees can incentivize recycling and waste reduction as disposal becomes more expensive.": "",
  "What are 'single-use plastics'?": "",
  "Plastic products designed to be used once and then discarded, such as bags, straws, bottles, and packaging": "",
  "Plastics that decompose after one use": "",
  "Plastics that can only be recycled once": "",
  "High-quality plastics used in medical equipment": "",
  "Single-use plastics are disposable plastic items intended for one-time use before disposal, including bags, straws, cups, cutlery, and packaging. They are a major contributor to plastic pollution in oceans and landfills.": "",
  "What is a 'circular economy'?": "",
  "An economy where all businesses are connected in a circle": "",
  "An economic model that designs out waste by keeping materials in use through reuse, repair, remanufacturing, and recycling": "",
  "A financial system based on circular currency": "",
  "An economy where goods are transported in circular routes": "",
  "A circular economy moves away from the linear 'take-make-dispose' model by designing products for durability, reuse, and recyclability, keeping materials circulating in the economy and minimizing waste sent to landfills.": "",
  "What does 'Superfund' (CERCLA) mean?": "",
  "A tax on consumer products to fund recycling programs": "",
  "A fund for building new landfills": "",
  "A federal program that identifies, investigates, and cleans up the nation's most contaminated hazardous waste sites": "",
  "A grant program for environmental education": "",
  "Superfund (CERCLA - Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act of 1980) authorizes the EPA to identify and clean up the most seriously contaminated hazardous waste sites in the United States.": "",
  "A city's only landfill is projected to reach capacity within five years. City officials are debating whether to open a new landfill or invest in waste reduction and recycling programs. Which approach would be more environmentally sustainable in the long term?": "",
  "Burning all waste in open pits to reduce volume according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Opening a larger landfill that will last longer under most circumstances involving landfill": "",
  "Shipping waste to other cities' landfills due to the well-established relationship between landfill trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Investing in comprehensive recycling, composting, and waste reduction programs to extend the existing landfill's life while reducing environmental impact": "",
  "Investing in waste reduction, recycling, and composting addresses the root problem by reducing the amount of waste needing disposal, extending landfill life, conserving resources, and reducing greenhouse gas emissions from decomposition.": "",
  "A community near an old, closed landfill discovers that groundwater wells show contamination from heavy metals and organic chemicals. The landfill predates modern environmental regulations. What likely caused the contamination?": "",
  "The old landfill lacked engineered liners and leachate collection systems, allowing contaminated liquid to seep into groundwater": "",
  "The chemicals were naturally present in the groundwater": "",
  "Nearby factories contaminated the groundwater, not the landfill": "",
  "Groundwater contamination cannot come from landfills": "",
  "Landfills built before modern regulations (pre-RCRA) often lacked impermeable liners and leachate collection systems, allowing rainwater to percolate through waste and carry dissolved contaminants into the underlying groundwater.": "",
  "A country exports large quantities of e-waste to developing nations where workers, including children, disassemble electronics by hand without protective equipment. Workers burn plastic casings to recover copper wire. What environmental justice issue does this represent?": "",
  "E-waste is not hazardous and poses no health risks": "",
  "Wealthy nations are exporting environmental and health hazards to vulnerable populations in poorer countries who bear the toxic burden": "",
  "Developing countries prefer this arrangement because it provides jobs": "",
  "This is an efficient recycling system that benefits everyone": "",
  "This represents environmental injustice where wealthy nations export their hazardous e-waste to developing countries. Workers face exposure to lead, mercury, cadmium, and toxic fumes from burning plastics without proper safety protections.": "",
  "A municipality implements a 'pay-as-you-throw' (PAYT) program where residents are charged based on the amount of trash they generate, while recycling pickup is free. What effect is this policy most likely to have?": "",
  "Residents will generate more waste": "",
  "Residents will stop using the waste collection service entirely": "",
  "Residents will reduce waste generation and increase recycling to lower their disposal costs": "",
  "The program will have no effect on waste behavior": "",
  "PAYT programs create a direct financial incentive to reduce waste and increase recycling. Studies show they typically reduce waste generation by 25-35% and increase recycling rates significantly by making disposal costs visible to consumers.": "",
  "A modern sanitary landfill captures methane gas produced by decomposing waste. What can this captured methane be used for?": "",
  "It can only be flared (burned off) and has no useful application": "",
  "It can be used to generate electricity, heat buildings, or be processed into pipeline-quality natural gas": "",
  "It must be released into the atmosphere because it is too dangerous to use": "",
  "It is converted into liquid fuel for vehicles": "",
  "Captured landfill methane (landfill gas) can be used as a renewable energy source to generate electricity, provide heating, or be upgraded to pipeline-quality renewable natural gas, turning a potent greenhouse gas into a useful energy resource.": "",
  "Researchers find that approximately 8 million metric tons of plastic enter the world's oceans each year. Most of this plastic originates from land-based sources. What is the most effective strategy to address ocean plastic pollution?": "",
  "Deploying ocean cleanup vessels to collect floating plastic": "",
  "Reducing plastic production and consumption at the source, improving waste management systems, and preventing plastic from entering waterways": "",
  "Developing bacteria that eat plastic in the ocean": "",
  "Sinking plastic to the ocean floor where it is less visible": "",
  "Preventing plastic from reaching the ocean is far more effective than cleanup. This requires reducing single-use plastics, improving waste collection infrastructure especially in developing coastal nations, and designing alternatives to disposable plastic products.": "",
  "A food manufacturer wants to reduce the environmental impact of its packaging. Currently, products use multilayer packaging made of plastic, aluminum, and paper bonded together. An advisor recommends switching to single-material packaging. Why would this change be beneficial?": "",
